- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

I've done some work that writes to `launch.json` without any problems (other than formatting, raised in another case). However I've just come to try and write to the normal user settings and it doesn't seem to be updating. From the release notes I think this should work (though I may have misunderstood):

> There is now `WorkspaceConfiguration#update` which allows extensions to add/update/remove configuration options. This should ease configuring the editor and extensions. For example, an extension would be able to configure a linter from a warning via a code action.

 Code looks like this:

```ts
let config = vs.workspace.getConfiguration("dart");

// Read current value
console.log(config.get("debugExternalLibraries", false));

// Update to true, globally
config.update("debugExternalLibraries", true, true /* false fails too */);

// Read new value
console.log(config.get("debugExternalLibraries"));

// Try re-fetching config in case stale
let config2 = vs.workspace.getConfiguration("dart");
console.log(config2.get("debugExternalLibraries"));
```

Output is:

```text
false
false
false
```

The value defaults to `false` in my `package.json` and is not set at the user or workspace level (I have no `settings.json` at the workspace level). After I set it to true (I've tried both globally and locally) it still always returns true. The user `settings.json` isn't updated when I do globally, and it is not created (I don't have one) in the project when I try at the workspace level.

